The xz backdoor was the final part of a campaign that spanned two years of operations. These operations were predominantly HUMINT style agent operations. There was an approach that lasted months before the Jia Tan persona was well positioned to be given a trusted role.

@ruairiSpain The names for the personas are all over the globe. Jia Tan, Jigar Kumar, Hans Jansen, and possibly Dennis Ens. Personally, I dont think the English used by the Kumar persona is Indian English. My gut feel is China, but it could be North Korea or anywhere really.

The way the campaign is falling apart under scrutiny is to be expected. They did not build a campaign to resist investigation, they built a campaign to avoid investigation. And they were successful. At no point in the campaign did they raise suspicion. It was just their bad luck.
@Vercingetronix Exactly.

Briefly, I want to address the issue of who is to blame. Easy ‚Äî the people behind the attack. Lasse, the maintainer of xz, was the target of a patient intelligence campaign that invested more resources into subverting him than anyone invested into his project.

It is important to remember that Lasse is blameless in this. There is no individual, and very very few organisations, able to detect, let alone resist!, the directed interest of an intelligence agency.

@billionsmustliv I agree, and I don‚Äôt think the solution is to never accept new people. No organisation (open source project, company, state agency, etc) is safe from an intelligence organisation with patience and resources. The lesson here is to find security solutions other than ‚Äútrust‚Äù

@billionsmustliv The goal should be able to trust people are well intentioned, and have processes in place to catch malicious activity regardless of the intent of who is involved. Paranoia is the wrong outcome.

In 2023 the operation to get the ifunc hook added to xz takes up the latter half of the year. They aren‚Äôt merged until October of 2023. There are cover operations that happen during this time as well, including an operation to lend credibility to the ifunc patch.

The entire campaign is very reasonably paced for an intelligence agency. They approach, get an agent in place, move the pieces into location, and then pull the trigger. Every stage is accomplished smoothly and with sufficient cover for action.
